<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-355-592  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 355 592.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Weekly  April 5 1990 n1208 p20(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The interface should not be just an afterthought.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Hicks, Richard.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The user interface is the essential element of a computer systemthat enables the system to achieve any functional efficiency andshould be integrated into the system rather than be an add-onproduct.andP;  Well-designed computer systems are sometimes less usefulthan they should be because of poorly planned application userinterfaces.andP;  Software developers can design their product to use aresident user interface to optimize the access to and utilizationof full range of their application's features.andP;  The softwaredesigner looks at a user interface as an 'illusion' thatfacilitates use while hiding the underlying code structure.andP;  Theillusion consists of overtly real objects (representing abstractprocesses) that can be manipulated to control those underlyingprocesses.andP;  Principles for user interface design includeexperimentation, use of familiar objects and creating a visualhierarchy.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     TutorialUser InterfaceSystem DesignImpact AnalysisRequirements AnalysisGoals and Objectives.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>